    "summary": "The Meidum Pyramid, located approximately 100 kilometers south of Cairo, represents one of the earliest attempts to construct a true smooth-sided pyramid in ancient Egypt, dating to the reign of Pharaoh Sneferu around 2610–2590 BC. The structure was originally built as a stepped pyramid of seven, later eight, tiers, and then modified — either by Sneferu or an earlier ruler — by filling in the steps with packing stones and encasing the whole in smooth limestone to achieve a true pyramid form. At some point, likely during or after the Old Kingdom, much of the outer casing collapsed, leaving the distinctive tower-like core visible today, surrounded by a massive pile of debris.\n\nThe collapse of the Meidum Pyramid is thought by many scholars to have been a catastrophic structural failure, possibly influencing the decision to alter the angle of the nearby Bent Pyramid at Dahshur mid-construction. The Meidum structure is therefore significant not as a triumph of engineering but as an instructive failure — one whose lessons contributed directly to the technical innovations that culminated in the successful smooth-sided pyramids built by Sneferu and his son Khufu, who commissioned the [[event:1708|Great Pyramid of Giza]].",
